= Blocks

Blocks are structural elements that organize content into distinct sections with specific formatting and behavior.

== Overview

Blocks provide a way to structure your document with various content types, each with its own rendering and substitution rules. They can contain paragraphs, lists, code, and other content elements.

== Block Types

This category includes the following block types:

* *Admonitions* - Callout blocks for notes, tips, warnings, and cautions
* *Callouts* - Numbered callouts for referencing specific parts of content
* *Code Blocks* - Source code with syntax highlighting
* *Example Blocks* - Example content with normal substitutions
* *Listing Blocks* - Preformatted text preserving whitespace
* *Literal Blocks* - Text output exactly as entered
* *Sidebar Blocks* - Aside content displayed outside the main flow
* *Tab Blocks* - Content organized into tabs
* *Accordion Blocks* - Collapsible sections of content
* *Step Blocks* - Numbered step-by-step instructions
* *Comment Blocks* - Comments that don't appear in output
* *Ordered Lists* - Numbered lists
* *Unordered Lists* - Bulleted lists
* *Definition Lists* - Term-definition pairs
* *Paragraphs* - Basic text paragraphs

== Usage

Each block type has its own syntax and use cases. Click on any feature above to see examples and learn how to use them in your documents.


